@invictusjs It would be good to also get your thoughts on this (or whether it could cause problems). Basically, when transferring an object from plasma manager A to plasma manager B (on two separate machines), the objects are sent over the network in chunks of `buf_size_` bytes. Relevant lines are https://github.com/ray-project/ray/blob/4a2d62e7efce3a38dabf1b08a868c6086f38811e/src/plasma/plasma_manager.cc#L546-L550.

So, we're currently calling `write` on pieces of size 4KB at a time. This PR is changing that number (potentially to 400KB).

@elibol Didn't you experiment with a benchmark in C where you call `write` in a loop and `read` on the other end. Did varying the chunk size from 4KB to 400KB cause any performance change? If not, any idea why it would make a difference in this setting?

**Potential problems.** It seems like this could make the call to `write` more likely to fail, since there may have to be more space in various buffers. The benchmarks done in this PR are in the case with no contention and only one object being transferred.

